$MELI's fee restructuring is the critical pivot point for MercadoLibreâ€™s 2026 thesis. It is shifting focus from the aggressive market share defense of 2025, which compressed margins to fight off Shopee and Temu, back to profitability and operational leverage. 

By replacing the flat subsidy on low-ticket items (<R$79) with variable operational costs and penalizing stagnant inventory, management is effectively forcing unit economics to improve and purging inefficient SKUs from their fulfillment centers to clear capacity for higher-turnover goods without additional capex. 

This should alleviate investor skepticism regarding margin durability. This successful pass-through of costs demonstrates pricing power and ecosystem lock-in, likely serving as the primary catalyst to help restore net income growth and expand operating margins in the second half of 2026 assuming seller churn remains manageable.
